Warm-up exercises with garden data

These exercises will reiterate what you learned in the Expanding the data wrangling toolkit tutorial. If you havent gone through the tutorial yet, you should do that first.

  1. Summarize the garden_harvest data to find the total harvest weight in pounds for each vegetable and day of week (HINT: use the wday() function from lubridate). Display the results so that the vegetables are rows but the days of the week are columns.
garden_harvest %>%
  group_by(vegetable, day_of_week=wday(date, label=TRUE)) %>%
  summarize(weight_lbs=sum(weight)*0.00220462)
  1. Summarize the garden_harvest data to find the total harvest in pound for each vegetable variety and then try adding the plot from the garden_planting table. This will not turn out perfectly. What is the problem? How might you fix it?

We have more rows that we originally had. We can fix this by getting rid of the variable plot because it is creating duplicates when we merge the datasets.

data("garden_planting")

garden_harvest %>%
  group_by(vegetable, variety) %>% 
  summarize(weight_lbs=sum(weight)*0.00220462) %>%
  left_join(garden_planting, 
            by= c("vegetable", "variety"))
  1. I would like to understand how much money I saved by gardening, for each vegetable type. Describe how I could use the garden_harvest and garden_spending datasets, along with data from somewhere like this to answer this question. You can answer this in words, referencing various join functions. You dont need R code but could provide some if its helpful.
data("garden_spending")

I would begin by merging the garden harvest and garden spending datasets so we can look at the weight of the harvests and compare it to the the price of our vegetables. I would then group by vegetable and find the total weight of each vegetable harvested and total price without tax for each vegetable. I would then compare it with the Whole Food prices by looking at their price per pound and multiplying it by how ever many pounds of the same vegetable that Lisa harvested. Lastly, I would find how much was saved by subtracting this number by the total price without tax for that same vegetable to see how much was saved compared to the Whole Foods price.

  1. Subset the data to tomatoes. Reorder the tomato varieties from smallest to largest first harvest date. Create a barplot of total harvest in pounds for each variety, in the new order.
garden_harvest %>%
  filter(vegetable %in% "tomatoes") %>%
  group_by(variety) %>%
  summarize(weight_lbs=sum(weight*0.00220462), first_harvest = min(date))  %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=fct_reorder(variety, first_harvest), x=weight_lbs)) +
  geom_col() + 
  labs(y="", x="weight(lbs)", title="Variety of Tomatoes by First Harvest date")

  1. In the garden_harvest data, create two new variables: one that makes the varieties lowercase and another that finds the length of the variety name. Arrange the data by vegetable and length of variety name (smallest to largest), with one row for each vegetable variety. HINT: use str_to_lower(), str_length(), and distinct().
garden_harvest %>%
  mutate(var_lower=str_to_lower(variety), var_length=str_length(variety)) %>%
  arrange(vegetable, (fct_infreq(variety))) %>%
  distinct(vegetable, var_length)
  1. In the garden_harvest data, find all distinct vegetable varieties that have er or ar in their name. HINT: str_detect() with an or statement (use the | for or) and distinct().
garden_harvest %>%
  mutate(var=str_detect(variety, "er|ar")) %>%
  filter(var==TRUE) %>%
  distinct(variety)

Bicycle-Use Patterns

In this activity, youll examine some factors that may influence the use of bicycles in a bike-renting program. The data come from Washington, DC and cover the last quarter of 2014.

Two data tables are available:

  • Trips contains records of individual rentals
  • Stations gives the locations of the bike rental stations

Here is the code to read in the data. We do this a little differently than usualy, which is why it is included here rather than at the top of this file. To avoid repeatedly re-reading the files, start the data import chunk with {r cache = TRUE} rather than the usual {r}.

data_site <- 
  "https://www.macalester.edu/~dshuman1/data/112/2014-Q4-Trips-History-Data.rds" 
Trips <- readRDS(gzcon(url(data_site)))
Stations<-read_csv("http://www.macalester.edu/~dshuman1/data/112/DC-Stations.csv")

NOTE: The Trips data table is a random subset of 10,000 trips from the full quarterly data. Start with this small data table to develop your analysis commands. When you have this working well, you should access the full data set of more than 600,000 events by removing -Small from the name of the data_site.

Temporal patterns

Its natural to expect that bikes are rented more at some times of day, some days of the week, some months of the year than others. The variable sdate gives the time (including the date) that the rental started. Make the following plots and interpret them:

  1. A density plot, which is a smoothed out histogram, of the events versus sdate. Use geom_density().
Trips %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=sdate)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of When Rentals Were Started")

  1. A density plot of the events versus time of day. You can use mutate() with lubridates hour() and minute() functions to extract the hour of the day and minute within the hour from sdate. Hint: A minute is 1/60 of an hour, so create a variable where 3:30 is 3.5 and 3:45 is 3.75.
Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals Over Time of Day")

  1. A bar graph of the events versus day of the week. Put day on the y-axis.
Trips %>%
  mutate(dow=wday(sdate, label=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=dow)) +
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(title="Events versus day of the week", y="", x="")

  1. Facet your graph from exercise 8. by day of the week. Is there a pattern?

There is a clear pattern, where the weekdays experience a drop in the middle and then come back up. On the weekends, the shape of the density plot is similar for Saturday and Sunday but set itself apart from the rest of the weekdays.

Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60) %>%
  mutate(dow=wday(sdate, label=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  facet_grid(.~dow) +
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals @ Different Times of Each Day of the Week")

The variable client describes whether the renter is a regular user (level Registered) or has not joined the bike-rental organization (Causal). The next set of exercises investigate whether these two different categories of users show different rental behavior and how client interacts with the patterns you found in the previous exercises.

  1. Change the graph from exercise 10 to set the fill aesthetic for geom_density() to the client variable. You should also set alpha = .5 for transparency and color=NA to suppress the outline of the density function.
Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60) %>%
  mutate(dow=weekdays(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day, fill=client)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5, color=NA) + 
  facet_grid(.~dow) + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals @ Different Times of Each Day of the Week")

  1. Change the previous graph by adding the argument position = position_stack() to geom_density(). In your opinion, is this better or worse in terms of telling a story? What are the advantages/disadvantages of each?

I think using position_stack is better because we can see it in the context of each of the two variables. One advantage is that it allows us to see which group is most frequent for a given value, however it makes it hard to understand the distribution of a group that is not on the bottom of the chart.

Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60) %>%
  mutate(dow=weekdays(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day, fill=client)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5, color=NA, position=position_stack())+ 
  facet_grid(.~dow) + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals @ Different Times of Each Day of the Week")

  1. In this graph, go back to using the regular density plot (without position = position_stack()). Add a new variable to the dataset called weekend which will be weekend if the day is Saturday or Sunday and weekday otherwise (HINT: use the ifelse() function and the wday() function from lubridate). Then, update the graph from the previous problem by faceting on the new weekend variable.
Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60,
         days_of_week=wday(sdate),
         weekend=ifelse(days_of_week>5, "weekend", "weekday")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day, fill=client)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5, color=NA)+ 
  facet_grid(.~weekend) + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals @ Different Times of Weekdays vs Weekends")

  1. Change the graph from the previous problem to facet on client and fill with weekday. What information does this graph tell you that the previous didnt? Is one graph better than the other?
Trips %>%
  mutate(time_of_day=hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60,
         days_of_week=wday(sdate),
         weekend=ifelse(days_of_week>5, "weekend", "weekday")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time_of_day, fill=weekend)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.5, color=NA)+ 
  facet_grid(.~client) + 
  labs(y="", x="", title="Distribution of Rentals @ Different Times for Casual vs Registered Riders")

Spatial patterns

  1. Use the latitude and longitude variables in Stations to make a visualization of the total number of departures from each station in the Trips data. Use either color or size to show the variation in number of departures. We will improve this plot next week when we learn about maps!
Trips %>% 
  group_by(sstation) %>%
  summarize(n_trips=n()) %>%
  left_join(Stations, by=c("sstation"="name")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=lat, x=long, size=n_trips)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.3) + 
  labs(size="# of trips", y="latitude", x="longitude")

  1. Only 14.4% of the trips in our data are carried out by casual users. Create a plot that shows which area(s) have stations with a much higher percentage of departures by casual users. What patterns do you notice? (Again, well improve this next week when we learn about maps).
Trips %>% 
  mutate(client2= client=="Casual") %>%
  group_by(sstation) %>%
  summarize(cas_percentage=sum(client2)/n()) %>%
  left_join(Stations, by=c("sstation"="name")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=lat, x=long, size=cas_percentage)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.3) + 
  labs(size="percentage of riders", y="latitude", x="longitude")

Spatiotemporal patterns

  1. Make a table with the ten station-date combinations (e.g., 14th & V St., 2014-10-14) with the highest number of departures, sorted from most departures to fewest. Save this to a new dataset and print out the dataset. Hint: as_date(sdate) converts sdate from date-time format to date format.
Trips %>%
  mutate(date=as_date(sdate)) %>%
  group_by(sstation, date) %>%
  summarize(departures=n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(departures)) %>%
  head(10)
  1. Use a join operation to make a table with only those trips whose departures match those top ten station-date combinations from the previous part.
top_ten <- Trips %>%
  mutate(date=as_date(sdate)) %>%
  group_by(sstation, date) %>%
  summarize(departures=n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(departures)) %>%
  head(10) 

Trips %>%
  mutate(date=as_date(sdate)) %>%
  inner_join(top_ten, by=c("sstation", "date"))
  1. Build on the code from the previous problem (ie. copy that code below and then %>% into the next step.) and group the trips by client type and day of the week (use the name, not the number). Find the proportion of trips by day within each client type (ie. the proportions for all 7 days within each client type add up to 1). Display your results so day of week is a column and there is a column for each client type. Interpret your results.
Trips %>%
  mutate(date=as_date(sdate)) %>%
  inner_join(top_ten, by = c("sstation", "date")) %>%
  mutate(day_of_week=wday(date, label=TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(day_of_week, client) %>%
  summarize(n_trips=n()) %>%
  group_by(client) %>% 
  mutate(prop=n_trips/sum(n_trips)) %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols=day_of_week, names_from=client, values_from=prop)
